    followUp: { interval: '2 weeks post-discharge, then 1 month, 3 months, 6 months, then annually', duration: 'Lifelong', tests: ['BP at every visit (target <130/80)', 'Lipid panel at 6 weeks and annually', 'HbA1c at 3 months and annually (if diabetic)', 'Carotid Doppler at 3-6 months if stenosis known', 'ECG at each visit (detect AF)', 'Holter/event monitor if cryptogenic stroke (paroxysmal AF detection)', 'Modified Rankin Scale (mRS) at 3 months', 'Mood screening (PHQ-9) at each visit'], specialistReview: true, specialistTiming: 'Neurology follow-up at 2 weeks and 3 months; at 6 months if functional limitation persists; annually for secondary prevention' },
    prognosis: 'Good functional outcome (mRS 0-2) at 3 months: 55-65% with thrombolysis, 70-80% with thrombectomy if LVO. Mortality: 12-20% at 30 days, 25-35% at 1 year. Poor prognostic factors: higher age, high NIHSS at presentation, large infarct core (ASPECTS <5), hyperglycaemia, atrial fibrillation, delayed treatment. Recurrence risk: 10-15% at 1 year, 25-40% at 5 years without optimal secondary prevention. With optimal secondary prevention (antiplatelet, statin, BP control, lifestyle): 50% relative risk reduction. Return to work: 40% at 1 year. Quality of life: 60% report good QOL at 1 year despite disability. In Kenya: mortality higher due to delayed presentation, limited thrombectomy access, and high post-stroke infection rates. Rehabilitation access limited - community-based programmes essential.',
